The paper deals with the complexity of counting problems in a bounded degree setting, which is a topic that falls under computational complexity theory (cs.CC). The use of Boolean constraint languages and the study of counting independent sets in bipartite graphs suggest that the paper may also be relevant to discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and graph theory (cs.CG). The analysis of degree bounds and the study of the complexity of approximation algorithms suggest that the paper may also be relevant to algorithms and data structures (cs.DS) and geometric topology (cs.GT).
